{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JMHsNKjqKoavsFf2xWuGUr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The CockroachDB cluster is experiencing liveness heartbeat failures. This is because the cluster nodes are having trouble reconnecting after the restart. However, I can see that pods are in \"Running\" state, which means CockroachDB started up - it's just struggling with the transition. Let me check if the TLS handshake issue is resolved:\n\nLooking at the logs - these are just quorum/heartbeat issues during startup. The key question is: is the TLS working? Let me check the readiness status. \n\nThe readiness probe failure earlier was \"Readiness probe failed: HTTP probe failed with statuscode: 503\" which is different from a connection refused. \n\nA 503 response actually indicates the node booted successfully with TLS enabled but isn't ready yet. The real problem was that pod 2 was trying to connect to pods 0 and 1 using TLS while they were still in insecure mode - that's what caused the handshake failure. Now that all three pods have been restarted with the updated TLS configuration, they should all be on the same page. But they're still not becoming ready after a couple minutes, so I need to verify they're all using the correct config revision.\n\nLet me look at the certificate permissions - CockroachDB has specific requirements here. When Kubernetes mounts secrets with `defaultMode: 256` (0400 in octal), all files end up with 0400 permissions, but CockroachDB expects the key files to be 0600 and cert files to be 0644. This permission mismatch could be preventing the nodes from starting properly. Let me dig into the pod logs to see if there are certificate-related errors or if something else is causing the node to fail.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3431,"cache_read_input_tokens":45814,"cac